\/wiki\/Blood_transfusion\" title=\"Blood transfusion\">transfuse blood<\/a> without endangering the patient\u2032s life. With <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Constantin_Levaditi\" title=\"Constantin Levaditi\">Constantin Levaditi<\/a> and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Erwin_Popper\" title=\"Erwin Popper\">Erwin Popper<\/a>, he discovered the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Polio_virus\" title=\"Polio virus\" class=\"mw-redirect\">polio virus<\/a>, in 1909. He received the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Aronson_Prize\" title=\"Aronson Prize\">Aronson Prize<\/a> in 1926. In 1930 he received the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize_in_Physiology_or_Medicine\" title=\"Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine\">Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine<\/a>. He was awarded a <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Lasker_Award\" title=\"Lasker Award\">Lasker Award<\/a> in 1946 posthumously and is recognized as the father of transfusion medicine.<\/p>","name":"Karl Landsteiner","place_of_birth":"Baden bei Wien , near Vienna (Austria)","place_of_death":"New York City","text":"Karl Landsteiner , Physiology or Medicine, 1930","year":1930.0}